# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: euclidean-gcd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] A **continued fraction** is a mathematical expression written as a fraction whose denominator contains a sum involving another fraction, which may itself be a simple or a continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] If this iteration (repetitive process) terminates with a simple fraction, the result is a **finite continued fraction**; if it continues indefinitely, the result is an **infinite continued fraction**.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The special case in which all numerators $\{a_{i}\}$ (see image) are equal to one, and all denominators $\{b_{i}\}$ are positive integers, is referred to as a simple (or regular) continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Any positive rational number can be expressed as a finite simple continued fraction, and any positive irrational number can be expressed as an infinite simple continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Different areas of mathematics use different terminology and notation for continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In number theory, the unqualified term *continued fraction* usually refers to simple continued fractions, whereas the general case is referred to as **generalized continued fractions**.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In complex analysis and numerical analysis, the general case is usually referred to by the unqualified term *continued fraction*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The numerators and denominators of continued fractions can be sequences $\{a_{i}\},\{b_{i}\}$ of numbers or functions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] If the sequence of convergents {*x**n*} approaches a limit, the continued fraction is convergent and has a definite value.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] If the sequence of convergents never approaches a limit, the continued fraction is divergent.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] It may diverge by oscillation (for example, the odd and even convergents may approach two different limits), or it may produce an infinite number of zero denominators *B**n*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The story of continued fractions begins with the Euclidean algorithm, a procedure for finding the greatest common divisor of two natural numbers *m* and *n*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] That algorithm introduced the idea of dividing to extract a new remainder – and then dividing by the new remainder repeatedly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Nearly two thousand years passed before Bombelli (1579) devised a technique for approximating the roots of quadratic equations with continued fractions in the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Just 24 years later, in 1613, Pietro Cataldi introduced the first formal notation for the generalized continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Late in the seventeenth century John Wallis introduced the term "continued fraction" into mathematical literature.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] New techniques for mathematical analysis (Newton's and Leibniz's calculus) had recently come onto the scene, and a generation of Wallis' contemporaries put the new phrase to use.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In 1748 Euler published a theorem showing that a particular kind of continued fraction is equivalent to a certain very general infinite series.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Euler's continued fraction formula is still the basis of many modern proofs of convergence of continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Continued fractions can also be applied to problems in number theory, and are especially useful in the study of Diophantine equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In the late eighteenth century Lagrange used continued fractions to construct the general solution of Pell's equation, thus answering a question that had fascinated mathematicians for more than a thousand years.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Lagrange's discovery implies that the canonical continued fraction expansion of the square root of every non-square integer is periodic and that, if the period is of length *p* > 1, it contains a palindromic string of length *p* − 1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In 1813 Gauss derived from complex-valued hypergeometric functions what are now called Gauss's continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] They can be used to express many elementary functions and some more advanced functions (such as the Bessel functions), as continued fractions that are rapidly convergent almost everywhere in the complex plane.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The long continued fraction expression displayed in the introduction is easy for an unfamiliar reader to interpret.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] However, it takes up a lot of space and can be difficult to typeset.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] So mathematicians have devised several alternative notations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Carl Friedrich Gauss evoked the more familiar infinite product ∏ when he devised this notation: $x=b_{0}+{\underset {i=1}{\overset {\infty }{\operatorname {K} }}}{\frac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}.$ Here, the "K" stands for *Kettenbruch*, the German word for "continued fraction".
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] This is probably the most compact and convenient way to express continued fractions; however, it is not widely used by English typesetters.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Here are some elementary results that are of fundamental importance in the further development of the analytic theory of continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Such an object is of little interest from the point of view adopted in mathematical analysis, so it is usually assumed that all *ai* ≠ 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] There is no need to place this restriction on the partial denominators bi.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] to relate the numerators and denominators of successive convergents *x**n* and *x**n* − 1 to one another.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The proof for this can be easily seen by induction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The equivalence transformation is perfectly general, but two particular cases deserve special mention.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] These two special cases of the equivalence transformation are enormously useful when the general convergence problem is analyzed.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] As mentioned in the introduction, the continued fraction $x=b_{0}+{\underset {i=1}{\overset {\infty }{\operatorname {K} }}}{\frac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}$ converges if the sequence of convergents {*x**n*} tends to a finite limit.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] This notion of convergence is very natural, but it is sometimes too restrictive.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] It is therefore useful to introduce the notion of general convergence of a continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Roughly speaking, this consists in replacing the $\operatorname {K} _{i=n}^{\infty }{\tfrac {a_{i}}{b_{i}}}$ part of the fraction by *w**n*, instead of by 0, to compute the convergents.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The convergents thus obtained are called *modified convergents*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] We say that the continued fraction *converges generally* if there exists a sequence $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ such that the sequence of modified convergents converges for all $\{w_{n}\}$ sufficiently distinct from $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The sequence $\{w_{n}^{*}\}$ is then called an *exceptional sequence* for the continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] See Chapter 2 of Lorentzen & Waadeland (1992) for a rigorous definition.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The Śleszyński–Pringsheim theorem provides a sufficient condition for absolute convergence.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] It is sometimes necessary to separate a continued fraction into its even and odd parts.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] For example, if the continued fraction diverges by oscillation between two distinct limit points *p* and *q*, then the sequence {*x*0, *x*2, *x*4, ...} must converge to one of these, and {*x*1, *x*3, *x*5, ...} must converge to the other.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In such a situation it may be convenient to express the original continued fraction as two different continued fractions, one of them converging to *p*, and the other converging to *q*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The formulas for the even and odd parts of a continued fraction can be written most compactly if the fraction has already been transformed so that all its partial denominators are unity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] More precisely, if the successive convergents of the continued fraction *x* are {*x*1, *x*2, *x*3, ...}, then the successive convergents of *x*even as written above are {*x*2, *x*4, *x*6, ...}, and the successive convergents of *x*odd are {*x*1, *x*3, *x*5, ...}.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] These recurrence relations are due to John Wallis (1616–1703) and Leonhard Euler (1707–1783).
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] These recurrence relations are simply a different notation for the relations obtained by Pietro Antonio Cataldi (1548-1626).
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Applying the fundamental recurrence formulas we find that the successive numerators *A**n* are {1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ...} and the successive denominators *B**n* are {1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, ...}, the Fibonacci numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Since all the partial numerators in this example are equal to one, the determinant formula assures us that the absolute value of the difference between successive convergents approaches zero quite rapidly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] A linear fractional transformation (LFT) is a complex function of the form $w=f(z)={\frac {az+b}{cz+d}},$ where z is a complex variable, and *a*, *b*, *c*, *d* are arbitrary complex constants such that *cz* + *d* ≠ 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] An additional restriction that *ad* ≠ *bc* is customarily imposed, to rule out the cases in which *w* = *f*(*z*) is a constant.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The linear fractional transformation, also known as a Möbius transformation, has many fascinating properties.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Four of these are of primary importance in developing the analytic theory of continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Here we use τ to represent each simple LFT, and we adopt the conventional circle notation for composition of functions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Defining a finite continued fraction as the image of a point under the iterated linear fractional transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) leads to an intuitively appealing geometric interpretation of infinite continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In the first of these equations the ratio tends toward ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ as z tends toward zero.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] In the second, the ratio tends toward ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ as z tends to infinity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] This leads us to our first geometric interpretation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] If the continued fraction converges, the successive convergents ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠ are eventually arbitrarily close together.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Since the linear fractional transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) is a continuous mapping, there must be a neighborhood of *z* = 0 that is mapped into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of **Τ*n***(0) = ⁠*An*/*Bn*⁠.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Similarly, there must be a neighborhood of the point at infinity which is mapped into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of **Τ*n***(∞) = ⁠*A**n*−1/*B**n*−1⁠.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] So if the continued fraction converges the transformation **Τ*n***(*z*) maps both very small z and very large z into an arbitrarily small neighborhood of x, the value of the continued fraction, as n gets larger and larger.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] For intermediate values of z, since the successive convergents are getting closer together we must have ${\frac {A_{n-1}}{B_{n-1}}}\approx {\frac {A_{n}}{B_{n}}}\quad \Rightarrow \quad {\frac {A_{n-1}}{A_{n}}}\approx {\frac {B_{n-1}}{B_{n}}}=k$ where k is a constant, introduced for convenience.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Intuitively, it is almost as if the convergent continued fraction maps the entire extended complex plane into a single point.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Notice that the sequence {**Τ*n***} lies within the automorphism group of the extended complex plane, since each **Τ*n*** is a linear fractional transformation for which *ab* ≠ *cd*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] And every member of that automorphism group maps the extended complex plane into itself: not one of the **Τ*n*** can possibly map the plane into a single point.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Yet in the limit the sequence {**Τ*n***} defines an infinite continued fraction which (if it converges) represents a single point in the complex plane.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] When an infinite continued fraction converges, the corresponding sequence {**Τ*n***} of LFTs "focuses" the plane in the direction of x, the value of the continued fraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] At each stage of the process a larger and larger region of the plane is mapped into a neighborhood of x, and the smaller and smaller region of the plane that's left over is stretched out ever more thinly to cover everything outside that neighborhood.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The sequence {**Τ*n***} may produce an infinite number of zero denominators Bi while also producing a subsequence of finite convergents.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] These finite convergents may not repeat themselves or fall into a recognizable oscillating pattern.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Or they may converge to a finite limit, or even oscillate among multiple finite limits.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] No matter how the finite convergents behave, the continued fraction defined by the sequence {**Τ*n***} diverges by oscillation with the point at infinity in this case.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The sequence {**Τ*n***} may produce no more than a finite number of zero denominators Bi. while the subsequence of finite convergents dances wildly around the plane in a pattern that never repeats itself and never approaches any finite limit either.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Interesting examples of cases 1 and 3 can be constructed by studying the simple continued fraction $x=1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+{\cfrac {z}{1+\ddots }}}}}}}}$ where z is any real number such that *z* < −⁠1/4⁠.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Euler's formula connecting continued fractions and series is the motivation for the fundamental inequalities, and also the basis of elementary approaches to the convergence problem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Here are two continued fractions that can be built via Euler's identity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] This last is based on an algorithm derived by Aleksei Nikolaevich Khovansky in the 1970s.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Here are three of π's best-known generalized continued fractions, the first and third of which are derived from their respective arctangent formulas above by setting *x* = *y* = 1 and multiplying by 4.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] The square root can also be expressed by a periodic continued fraction, but the above form converges more quickly with the proper *x* and *y*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] More details on this technique can be found in *General Method for Extracting Roots using (Folded) Continued Fractions*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Another meaning for **generalized continued fraction** is a generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] For example, there is a close relationship between the simple continued fraction in canonical form for the irrational real number *α*, and the way integer lattice points in two dimensions lie to either side of the line *y* = *αx*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Generalizing this idea, one might ask about something related to lattice points in three or more dimensions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] One reason to study this area is to quantify the mathematical coincidence idea; for example, for monomials in several real numbers, take the logarithmic form and consider how small it can be.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Another reason is to find a possible solution to Hermite's problem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] There have been numerous attempts to construct a generalized theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/continued-fraction] Notable efforts in this direction were made by Felix Klein (the Klein polyhedron), Georges Poitou and George Szekeres.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In mathematics, the **Euclidean algorithm**, or **Euclid's algorithm**, is an efficient method for computing the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two integers, the largest number that divides them both without a remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is named after the ancient Greek mathematician Euclid, who first described it in his *Elements* (c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is an example of an *algorithm*, and is one of the oldest algorithms in common use.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It can be used to reduce fractions to their simplest form, and is a part of many other number-theoretic and cryptographic calculations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm is based on the principle that the greatest common divisor of two numbers does not change if the larger number is replaced by its difference with the smaller number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since this replacement reduces the larger of the two numbers, repeating this process gives successively smaller pairs of numbers until the two numbers become equal.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] When that occurs, that number is the GCD of the original two numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By reversing the steps or using the extended Euclidean algorithm, the GCD can be expressed as a linear combination of the two original numbers, that is the sum of the two numbers, each multiplied by an integer (for example, 21 = 5 × 105 + (−2) × 252).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The fact that the GCD can always be expressed in this way is known as Bézout's identity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The version of the Euclidean algorithm described above—which follows Euclid's original presentation—may require many subtraction steps to find the GCD when one of the given numbers is much bigger than the other.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A more efficient version of the algorithm shortcuts these steps, instead replacing the larger of the two numbers by its remainder when divided by the smaller of the two (with this version, the algorithm stops when reaching a zero remainder).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] With this improvement, the algorithm never requires more steps than five times the number of digits (base 10) of the smaller integer.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This was proven by Gabriel Lamé in 1844 (Lamé's Theorem), and marks the beginning of computational complexity theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Additional methods for improving the algorithm's efficiency were developed in the 20th century.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has many theoretical and practical applications.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] It is used for reducing fractions to their simplest form and for performing division in modular arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Computations using this algorithm form part of the cryptographic protocols that are used to secure internet communications, and in methods for breaking these cryptosystems by factoring large composite numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm may be used to solve Diophantine equations, such as finding numbers that satisfy multiple congruences according to the Chinese remainder theorem, to construct continued fractions, and to find accurate rational approximations to real numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finally, it can be used as a basic tool for proving theorems in number theory such as Lagrange's four-square theorem and the uniqueness of prime factorizations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The original algorithm was described only for natural numbers and geometric lengths (real numbers), but the algorithm was generalized in the 19th century to other types of numbers, such as Gaussian integers and polynomials of one variable.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This led to modern abstract algebraic notions such as Euclidean domains.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm calculates the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two natural numbers a and b.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g is the largest natural number that divides both a and b without leaving a remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Synonyms for GCD include *greatest common factor* (GCF), *highest common factor* (HCF), *highest common divisor* (HCD), and *greatest common measure* (GCM).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor is often written as gcd(*a*, *b*) or, more simply, as (*a*, *b*), although the latter notation is ambiguous, also used for concepts such as an ideal in the ring of integers, which is closely related to GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If gcd(*a*, *b*) = 1, then a and b are said to be coprime (or relatively prime).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This property does not imply that a or b are themselves prime numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, 6 and 35 factor as 6 = 2 × 3 and 35 = 5 × 7, so they are not prime, but their prime factors are different, so 6 and 35 are coprime, with no common factors other than 1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since a and b are both multiples of g, they can be written *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng*, and there is no larger number *G* > *g* for which this is true.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The natural numbers m and n must be coprime, since any common factor could be factored out of m and n to make g greater.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, any other number c that divides both a and b must also divide g.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g of a and b is the unique (positive) common divisor of a and b that is divisible by any other common divisor c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor can be visualized as follows.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Consider a rectangular area a by b, and any common divisor c that divides both a and b exactly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sides of the rectangle can be divided into segments of length c, which divides the rectangle into a grid of squares of side length c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD g is the largest value of c for which this is possible.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For illustration, a 24×60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: 1×1 squares, 2×2 squares, 3×3 squares, 4×4 squares, 6×6 squares or 12×12 squares.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A 24×60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of 12×12 squares, with two squares along one edge (24/12 = 2) and five squares along the other (60/12 = 5).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor of two numbers a and b is the product of the prime factors shared by the two numbers, where each prime factor can be repeated as many times as it divides both a and b.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, since 1386 can be factored into 2 × 3 × 3 × 7 × 11, and 3213 can be factored into 3 × 3 × 3 × 7 × 17, the GCD of 1386 and 3213 equals 63 = 3 × 3 × 7, the product of their shared prime factors (with 3 repeated since 3 × 3 divides both).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If two numbers have no common prime factors, their GCD is 1 (obtained here as an instance of the empty product); in other words, they are coprime.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A key advantage of the Euclidean algorithm is that it can find the GCD efficiently without having to compute the prime factors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Factorization of large integers is believed to be a computationally very difficult problem, and the security of many widely used cryptographic protocols is based upon its infeasibility.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Another definition of the GCD is helpful in advanced mathematics, particularly ring theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The greatest common divisor g of two nonzero numbers a and b is also their smallest positive integral linear combination, that is, the smallest positive number of the form *ua* + *vb* where u and v are integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The set of all integral linear combinations of a and b is actually the same as the set of all multiples of g (mg, where m is an integer).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In modern mathematical language, the ideal generated by a and b is the ideal generated by g alone (an ideal generated by a single element is called a principal ideal, and all ideals of the integers are principal ideals).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Some properties of the GCD are in fact easier to see with this description, for instance the fact that any common divisor of a and b also divides the GCD (it divides both terms of *ua* + *vb*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The equivalence of this GCD definition with the other definitions is described below.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD of three or more numbers equals the product of the prime factors common to all the numbers, but it can also be calculated by repeatedly taking the GCDs of pairs of numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, Euclid's algorithm, which computes the GCD of two integers, suffices to calculate the GCD of arbitrarily many integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Because the sequence of non-negative integers $\{r_{k}\}$ is strictly decreasing, it eventually must terminate.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, since $r_{k}\geq 0$ for every $k,$ and each $r_{k}$ is an integer that is strictly smaller than the preceding $r_{k-1},$ there eventually cannot be a non-negative integer smaller than zero, and hence the algorithm must terminate.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In fact, the algorithm will always terminate at the *n*th step with $r_{n}$ equal to zero.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To illustrate, suppose the GCD of 1071 and 462 is requested.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, dropping any ordering between the first two integers does not affect the conclusion that the sequence must eventually terminate because the next remainder will always satisfy $r_{0}<b$ and everything continues as above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The only modifications that need to be made are that $r_{k}<r_{k-1}$ only for $k\geq 0,$ and that the sub-sequence of non-negative integers $\{r_{k-1}\}$ for $k\geq 0$ is strictly decreasing, therefore excluding $a=r_{-2}$ from both statements.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The existence of a step N such that $r_{N}=0$ follows from the condition $|r_{i}|<|r_{i-1}|$ , for $i\geq 1$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This ensures that the algorithm terminates.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In particular, the largest of their common divisors are the same.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Property 2 shows that the $\gcd$ of the pairs remains invariant.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In particular, the $\gcd$ of the first pair $(a,b)$ and the last pair $(r_{N-1},0)$ are the same.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For illustration, the Euclidean algorithm can be used to find the greatest common divisor of *a* = 1071 and *b* = 462.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To begin, multiples of 462 are subtracted from 1071 until the remainder is less than 462.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then multiples of 147 are subtracted from 462 until the remainder is less than 147.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then multiples of 21 are subtracted from 147 until the remainder is less than 21.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since the last remainder is zero, the algorithm ends with 21 as the greatest common divisor of 1071 and 462.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This agrees with the gcd(1071, 462) found by prime factorization above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm can be visualized in terms of the tiling analogy given above for the greatest common divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Assume that we wish to cover an *a*×*b* rectangle with square tiles exactly, where *a* is the larger of the two numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] We first attempt to tile the rectangle using *b*×*b* square tiles; however, this leaves an *r*0×*b* residual rectangle untiled, where *r*0 < *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] We then attempt to tile the residual rectangle with *r*0×*r*0 square tiles.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This leaves a second residual rectangle *r*1×*r*0, which we attempt to tile using *r*1×*r*1 square tiles, and so on.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sequence ends when there is no residual rectangle, i.e., when the square tiles cover the previous residual rectangle exactly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The length of the sides of the smallest square tile is the GCD of the dimensions of the original rectangle.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, the smallest square tile in the adjacent figure is 21×21 (shown in red), and 21 is the GCD of 1071 and 462, the dimensions of the original rectangle (shown in green).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where the *r**k* is non-negative and is strictly less than the absolute value of *r**k*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The theorem which underlies the definition of the Euclidean division ensures that such a quotient and remainder always exist and are unique.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Euclid's original version of the algorithm, the quotient and remainder are found by repeated subtraction; that is, *r**k*−1 is subtracted from *r**k*−2 repeatedly until the remainder *r**k* is smaller than *r**k*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] After that *r**k* and *r**k*−1 are exchanged and the process is iterated.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclidean division reduces all the steps between two exchanges into a single step, which is thus more efficient.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Moreover, the quotients are not needed, thus one may replace Euclidean division by the modulo operation, which gives only the remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Implementations of the algorithm may be expressed in pseudocode.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] At the beginning of the *k*th iteration, the variable *b* holds the latest remainder *r**k*−1, whereas the variable *a* holds its predecessor, *r**k*−2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The step *b* := *a* mod *b* is equivalent to the above recursion formula *r**k* ≡ *r**k*−2 mod *r**k*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The temporary variable *t* holds the value of *r**k*−1 while the next remainder *r**k* is being calculated.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] At the end of the loop iteration, the variable *b* holds the remainder *r**k*, whereas the variable *a* holds its predecessor, *r**k*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the subtraction-based version, which was Euclid's original version, the remainder calculation (`b := a **mod** b`) is replaced by repeated subtraction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The variables *a* and *b* alternate holding the previous remainders *r**k*−1 and *r**k*−2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Assume that *a* is larger than *b* at the beginning of an iteration; then *a* equals *r**k*−2, since *r**k*−2 > *r**k*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] During the loop iteration, *a* is reduced by multiples of the previous remainder *b* until *a* is smaller than *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Then *b* is reduced by multiples of *a* until it is again smaller than *a*, giving the next remainder *r**k*+1, and so on.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The recursive version is based on the equality of the GCDs of successive remainders and the stopping condition gcd(*r**N*−1, 0) = *r**N*−1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In another version of Euclid's algorithm, the quotient at each step is increased by one if the resulting negative remainder is smaller in magnitude than the typical positive remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Leopold Kronecker has shown that this version requires the fewest steps of any version of Euclid's algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] More generally, it has been proven that, for every input numbers *a* and *b*, the number of steps is minimal if and only if *q**k* is chosen in order that $\left|{\frac {r_{k+1}}{r_{k}}}\right|<{\frac {1}{\varphi }}\sim 0.618,$ where $\varphi$ is the golden ratio.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm is one of the oldest algorithms in common use.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] 300 BC), specifically in Book 7 (Propositions 1–2) and Book 10 (Propositions 2–3).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Book 7, the algorithm is formulated for integers, whereas in Book 10, it is formulated for lengths of line segments.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] (In modern usage, one would say it was formulated there for real numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] But lengths, areas, and volumes, represented as real numbers in modern usage, are not measured in the same units and there is no natural unit of length, area, or volume; the concept of real numbers was unknown at that time.) The latter algorithm is geometrical.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD of two lengths *a* and *b* corresponds to the greatest length *g* that measures *a* and *b* evenly; in other words, the lengths *a* and *b* are both integer multiples of the length *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm was probably not discovered by Euclid, who compiled results from earlier mathematicians in his *Elements*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] L. van der Waerden suggests that Book VII derives from a textbook on number theory written by mathematicians in the school of Pythagoras.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm was probably known by Eudoxus of Cnidus (about 375 BC).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The algorithm may even pre-date Eudoxus, judging from the use of the technical term ἀνθυφαίρεσις (*anthyphairesis*, reciprocal subtraction) in works by Euclid and Aristotle.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Claude Brezinski, following remarks by Pappus of Alexandria, credits the algorithm to Theaetetus (c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Centuries later, Euclid's algorithm was discovered independently both in India and in China, primarily to solve Diophantine equations that arose in astronomy and making accurate calendars.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the late 5th century, the Indian mathematician and astronomer Aryabhata described the algorithm as the "pulverizer", perhaps because of its effectiveness in solving Diophantine equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Although a special case of the Chinese remainder theorem had already been described in the Chinese book *Sunzi Suanjing*, the general solution was published by Qin Jiushao in his 1247 book *Shushu Jiuzhang* (數書九章 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm was first described *numerically* and popularized in Europe in the second edition of Bachet's *Problèmes plaisants et délectables* (*Pleasant and enjoyable problems*, 1624).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In Europe, it was likewise used to solve Diophantine equations and in developing continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The extended Euclidean algorithm was published by the English mathematician Nicholas Saunderson, who attributed it to Roger Cotes as a method for computing continued fractions efficiently.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm led to the development of new number systems, such as Gaussian integers and Eisenstein integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1815, Carl Gauss used the Euclidean algorithm to demonstrate unique factorization of Gaussian integers, although his work was first published in 1832.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Gauss mentioned the algorithm in his *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* (published 1801), but only as a method for continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet seems to have been the first to describe the Euclidean algorithm as the basis for much of number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Lejeune Dirichlet noted that many results of number theory, such as unique factorization, would hold true for any other system of numbers to which the Euclidean algorithm could be applied.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Lejeune Dirichlet's lectures on number theory were edited and extended by Richard Dedekind, who used Euclid's algorithm to study algebraic integers, a new general type of number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, Dedekind was the first to prove Fermat's two-square theorem using the unique factorization of Gaussian integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Dedekind also defined the concept of a Euclidean domain, a number system in which a generalized version of the Euclidean algorithm can be defined (as described below).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the closing decades of the 19th century, the Euclidean algorithm gradually became eclipsed by Dedekind's more general theory of ideals.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Other applications of Euclid's algorithm were developed in the 19th century.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1829, Charles Sturm showed that the algorithm was useful in the Sturm chain method for counting the real roots of polynomials in any given interval.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm was the first integer relation algorithm, which is a method for finding integer relations between commensurate real numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Several novel integer relation algorithms have been developed, such as the algorithm of Helaman Ferguson and R.W.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In 1969, Cole and Davie developed a two-player game based on the Euclidean algorithm, called *The Game of Euclid*, which has an optimal strategy.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The players begin with two piles of *a* and *b* stones.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The players take turns removing *m* multiples of the smaller pile from the larger.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, if the two piles consist of *x* and *y* stones, where *x* is larger than *y*, the next player can reduce the larger pile from *x* stones to *x* − *my* stones, as long as the latter is a nonnegative integer.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The winner is the first player to reduce one pile to zero stones.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity states that the greatest common divisor *g* of two integers *a* and *b* can be represented as a linear sum of the original two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, it is always possible to find integers *s* and *t* such that *g* = *sa* + *tb*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* can be calculated from the quotients *q*0, *q*1, etc. by reversing the order of equations in Euclid's algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Substituting these formulae for *r**N*−2 and *r**N*−3 into the first equation yields *g* as a linear sum of the remainders *r**N*−4 and *r**N*−5.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] After all the remainders *r*0, *r*1, etc. have been substituted, the final equation expresses *g* as a linear sum of *a* and *b*, so that *g* = *sa* + *tb*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm, and thus Bézout's identity, can be generalized to the context of Euclidean domains.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity provides yet another definition of the greatest common divisor *g* of two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Consider the set of all numbers *ua* + *vb*, where *u* and *v* are any two integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since *a* and *b* are both divisible by *g*, every number in the set is divisible by *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, every number of the set is an integer multiple of *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This is true for every common divisor of *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] However, unlike other common divisors, the greatest common divisor is a member of the set; by Bézout's identity, choosing *u* = *s* and *v* = *t* gives *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A smaller common divisor cannot be a member of the set, since every member of the set must be divisible by *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Conversely, any multiple *m* of *g* can be obtained by choosing *u* = *ms* and *v* = *mt*, where *s* and *t* are the integers of Bézout's identity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, the set of all numbers *ua* + *vb* is equivalent to the set of multiples *m* of *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In other words, the set of all possible sums of integer multiples of two numbers (*a* and *b*) is equivalent to the set of multiples of gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The GCD is said to be the generator of the ideal of *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This GCD definition led to the modern abstract algebraic concepts of a principal ideal (an ideal generated by a single element) and a principal ideal domain (a domain in which every ideal is a principal ideal).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Certain problems can be solved using this result.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, consider two measuring cups of volume *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By adding/subtracting *u* multiples of the first cup and *v* multiples of the second cup, any volume *ua* + *vb* can be measured out.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] These volumes are all multiples of *g* = gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* of Bézout's identity can be computed efficiently using the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Using this recursion, Bézout's integers *s* and *t* are given by *s* = *s**N* and *t* = *t**N*, where *N* + 1 is the step on which the algorithm terminates with *r**N*+1 = 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The validity of this approach can be shown by induction.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The integers *s* and *t* can also be found using an equivalent matrix method.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To express *g* as a linear sum of *a* and *b*, both sides of this equation can be multiplied by the inverse of the matrix **M**.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The determinant of **M** equals (−1)*N*+1, since it equals the product of the determinants of the quotient matrices, each of which is negative one.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The matrix method is as efficient as the equivalent recursion, with two multiplications and two additions per step of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Bézout's identity is essential to many applications of Euclid's algorithm, such as demonstrating the unique factorization of numbers into prime factors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] To illustrate this, suppose that a number *L* can be written as a product of two factors *u* and *v*, that is, *L* = *uv*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since *w* divides both terms on the right-hand side, it must also divide the left-hand side, *v*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Specifically, if a prime number divides *L*, then it must divide at least one factor of *L*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Conversely, if a number *w* is coprime to each of a series of numbers *a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n*, then *w* is also coprime to their product, *a*1 × *a*2 × ... × *a**n*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclid's lemma suffices to prove that every number has a unique factorization into prime numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since each prime *p* divides *L* by assumption, it must also divide one of the *q* factors; since each *q* is prime as well, it must be that *p* = *q*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Iteratively dividing by the *p* factors shows that each *p* has an equal counterpart *q*; the two prime factorizations are identical except for their order.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The unique factorization of numbers into primes has many applications in mathematical proofs, as shown below.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Diophantine equations are equations in which the solutions are restricted to integers; they are named after the 3rd-century Alexandrian mathematician Diophantus.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where *a*, *b* and *c* are given integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Let *g* be the greatest common divisor of *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Both terms in *ax* + *by* are divisible by *g*; therefore, *c* must also be divisible by *g*, or the equation has no solutions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] where *s* and *t* can be found by the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This provides one solution to the Diophantine equation, *x*1 = *s* (*c*/*g*) and *y*1 = *t* (*c*/*g*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In general, a linear Diophantine equation has no solutions, or an infinite number of solutions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Therefore, the smallest difference between two *x* solutions is *b*/*g*, whereas the smallest difference between two *y* solutions is *a*/*g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] By allowing *u* to vary over all possible integers, an infinite family of solutions can be generated from a single solution (*x*1, *y*1).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] If the solutions are required to be *positive* integers (*x* > 0, *y* > 0), only a finite number of solutions may be possible.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This restriction on the acceptable solutions allows some systems of Diophantine equations with more unknowns than equations to have a finite number of solutions; this is impossible for a system of linear equations when the solutions can be any real number (see Underdetermined system).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A finite field is a set of numbers with four generalized operations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The operations are called addition, subtraction, multiplication and division and have their usual properties, such as commutativity, associativity and distributivity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] An example of a finite field is the set of 13 numbers {0, 1, 2, ..., 12} using modular arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In this field, the results of any mathematical operation (addition, subtraction, multiplication, or division) is reduced modulo 13; that is, multiples of 13 are added or subtracted until the result is brought within the range 0–12.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] For example, the result of 5 × 7 = 35 mod 13 = 9.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Such finite fields can be defined for any prime *p*; using more sophisticated definitions, they can also be defined for any power *m* of a prime *p**m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finite fields are often called Galois fields, and are abbreviated as GF(*p*) or GF(*p**m*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In such a field with *m* numbers, every nonzero element *a* has a unique modular multiplicative inverse, *a*−1 such that *aa*−1 = *a*−1*a* ≡ 1 mod *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This equation can be solved by the Euclidean algorithm, as described above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Finding multiplicative inverses is an essential step in the RSA algorithm, which is widely used in electronic commerce; specifically, the equation determines the integer used to decrypt the message.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Although the RSA algorithm uses rings rather than fields, the Euclidean algorithm can still be used to find a multiplicative inverse where one exists.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm also has other applications in error-correcting codes; for example, it can be used as an alternative to the Berlekamp–Massey algorithm for decoding BCH and Reed–Solomon codes, which are based on Galois fields.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Euclid's algorithm can also be used to solve multiple linear Diophantine equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Such equations arise in the Chinese remainder theorem, which describes a novel method to represent an integer *x*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The goal is to determine *x* from its *N* remainders *x**i*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Thus, each *M**i* is the product of all the moduli *except* *m**i*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Since these numbers *h**i* are the multiplicative inverses of the *M**i*, they may be found using Euclid's algorithm as described in the previous subsection.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm can be used to arrange the set of all positive rational numbers into an infinite binary search tree, called the Stern–Brocot tree.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] A step of the Euclidean algorithm that replaces the first of the two numbers corresponds to a step in the tree from a node to its right child, and a step that replaces the second of the two numbers corresponds to a step in the tree from a node to its left child.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The sequence of steps constructed in this way does not depend on whether *a*/*b* is given in lowest terms, and forms a path from the root to a node containing the number *a*/*b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] This fact can be used to prove that each positive rational number appears exactly once in this tree.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has almost the same relationship to another binary tree on the rational numbers called the Calkin–Wilf tree.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The difference is that the path is reversed: instead of producing a path from the root of the tree to a target, it produces a path from the target to the root.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm has a close relationship with continued fractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The last term on the right-hand side always equals the inverse of the left-hand side of the next equation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The final ratio of remainders *r**k*/*r**k*−1 can always be replaced using the next equation in the series, up to the final equation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] In the worked example above, the gcd(1071, 462) was calculated, and the quotients *q**k* were 2, 3 and 7, respectively.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Calculating a greatest common divisor is an essential step in several integer factorization algorithms, such as Pollard's rho algorithm, Shor's algorithm, Dixon's factorization method and the Lenstra elliptic curve factorization.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] The Euclidean algorithm may be used to find this GCD efficiently.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p01] Continued fraction factorization uses continued fractions, which are determined using Euclid's algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The computational efficiency of Euclid's algorithm has been studied thoroughly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This efficiency can be described by the number of division steps the algorithm requires, multiplied by the computational expense of each step.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first known analysis of Euclid's algorithm is due to A.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Reynaud in 1811, who showed that the number of division steps on input (*u*, *v*) is bounded by *v*; later he improved this to *v*/2 + 2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finck showed that the number of division steps is at most 2 log2 *v* + 1, and hence Euclid's algorithm runs in time polynomial in the size of the input. Émile Léger, in 1837, studied the worst case, which is when the inputs are consecutive Fibonacci numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finck's analysis was refined by Gabriel Lamé in 1844, who showed that the number of steps required for completion is never more than five times the number *h* of base-10 digits of the smaller number *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In the uniform cost model (suitable for analyzing the complexity of gcd calculation on numbers that fit into a single machine word), each step of the algorithm takes constant time, and Lamé's analysis implies that the total running time is also *O*(*h*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, in a model of computation suitable for computation with larger numbers, the computational expense of a single remainder computation in the algorithm can be as large as *O*(*h*2).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In this case the total time for all of the steps of the algorithm can be analyzed using a telescoping series, showing that it is also *O*(*h*2).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Modern algorithmic techniques based on the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm for fast integer multiplication can be used to speed this up, leading to quasilinear algorithms for the GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The number of steps to calculate the GCD of two natural numbers, *a* and *b*, may be denoted by *T*(*a*, *b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If *g* is the GCD of *a* and *b*, then *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng* for two coprime numbers *m* and *n*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] as may be seen by dividing all the steps in the Euclidean algorithm by *g*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] By the same argument, the number of steps remains the same if *a* and *b* are multiplied by a common factor *w*: *T*(*a*, *b*) = *T*(*wa*, *wb*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Therefore, the number of steps *T* may vary dramatically between neighboring pairs of numbers, such as T(*a*, *b*) and T(*a*, *b* + 1), depending on the size of the two GCDs.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the Euclidean algorithm requires *N* steps for a pair of natural numbers *a* > *b* > 0, the smallest values of *a* and *b* for which this is true are the Fibonacci numbers *F**N*+2 and *F**N*+1, respectively.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] More precisely, if the Euclidean algorithm requires *N* steps for the pair *a* > *b*, then one has *a* ≥ *F**N*+2 and *b* ≥ *F**N*+1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If *N* = 1, *b* divides *a* with no remainder; the smallest natural numbers for which this is true is *b* = 1 and *a* = 2, which are *F*2 and *F*3, respectively.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Now assume that the result holds for all values of *N* up to *M* − 1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first step of the *M*-step algorithm is *a* = *q*0*b* + *r*0, and the Euclidean algorithm requires *M* − 1 steps for the pair *b* > *r*0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This proof, published by Gabriel Lamé in 1844, represents the beginning of computational complexity theory, and also the first practical application of the Fibonacci numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This result suffices to show that the number of steps in Euclid's algorithm can never be more than five times the number of its digits (base 10).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For if the algorithm requires *N* steps, then *b* is greater than or equal to *F**N*+1 which in turn is greater than or equal to *φ**N*−1, where *φ* is the golden ratio.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Thus, the Euclidean algorithm always needs less than *O*(*h*) divisions, where *h* is the number of digits in the smaller number *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The average number of steps taken by the Euclidean algorithm has been defined in three different ways.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, since *T*(*a*, *b*) fluctuates dramatically with the GCD of the two numbers, the averaged function *T*(*a*) is likewise "noisy".
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] There are *φ*(*a*) coprime integers less than *a*, where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] with the residual error being of order *a*−(1/6)+*ε*, where *ε* is infinitesimal.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *γ* is the Euler–Mascheroni constant and *ζ*′ is the derivative of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The leading coefficient (12/π2) ln 2 was determined by two independent methods.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The computational expense of dividing *h*-bit numbers scales as *O*(*h*(*ℓ* + 1)), where ℓ is the length of the quotient.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For comparison, Euclid's original subtraction-based algorithm can be much slower.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A single integer division is equivalent to the quotient *q* number of subtractions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the ratio of *a* and *b* is very large, the quotient is large and many subtractions will be required.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the quotients are very likely to be small integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The probability of a given quotient *q* is approximately ln |*u*/(*u* − 1)| where *u* = (*q* + 1)2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For illustration, the probability of a quotient of 1, 2, 3, or 4 is roughly 41.5%, 17.0%, 9.3%, and 5.9%, respectively.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the operation of subtraction is faster than division, particularly for large numbers, the subtraction-based Euclid's algorithm is competitive with the division-based version.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This is exploited in the binary version of Euclid's algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Combining the estimated number of steps with the estimated computational expense per step shows that the Euclid's algorithm grows quadratically (*h*2) with the average number of digits *h* in the initial two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Euclid's algorithm is widely used in practice, especially for small numbers, due to its simplicity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For comparison, the efficiency of alternatives to Euclid's algorithm may be determined.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] One inefficient approach to finding the GCD of two natural numbers *a* and *b* is to calculate all their common divisors; the GCD is then the largest common divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The common divisors can be found by dividing both numbers by successive integers from 2 to the smaller number *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The number of steps of this approach grows linearly with *b*, or exponentially in the number of digits.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Another inefficient approach is to find the prime factors of one or both numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] As noted above, the GCD equals the product of the prime factors shared by the two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Present methods for prime factorization are also inefficient; many modern cryptography systems even rely on that inefficiency.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The binary GCD algorithm is an efficient alternative that substitutes division with faster operations by exploiting the binary representation used by computers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] However, this alternative also scales like *O*(*h*²).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] It is generally faster than the Euclidean algorithm on real computers, even though it scales in the same way.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Additional efficiency can be gleaned by examining only the leading digits of the two numbers *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The binary algorithm can be extended to other bases (*k*-ary algorithms), with up to fivefold increases in speed.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Lehmer's GCD algorithm uses the same general principle as the binary algorithm to speed up GCD computations in arbitrary bases.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A recursive approach for very large integers (with more than 25,000 digits) leads to quasilinear integer GCD algorithms, such as those of Schönhage, and Stehlé and Zimmermann.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] These algorithms exploit the 2×2 matrix form of the Euclidean algorithm given above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] These quasilinear methods generally scale as *O*(*h* log *h*2 log log *h*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Although the Euclidean algorithm is used to find the greatest common divisor of two natural numbers (positive integers), it may be generalized to the real numbers, and to other mathematical objects, such as polynomials, quadratic integers and Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In the latter cases, the Euclidean algorithm is used to demonstrate the crucial property of unique factorization, i.e., that such numbers can be factored uniquely into irreducible elements, the counterparts of prime numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Unique factorization is essential to many proofs of number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Euclid's algorithm can be applied to real numbers, as described by Euclid in Book 10 of his *Elements*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The goal of the algorithm is to identify a real number g such that two given real numbers, a and b, are integer multiples of it: *a* = *mg* and *b* = *ng*, where m and n are integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This identification is equivalent to finding an integer relation among the real numbers a and b; that is, it determines integers s and t such that *sa* + *tb* = 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If such an equation is possible, *a* and *b* are called commensurable lengths, otherwise they are incommensurable lengths.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The real-number Euclidean algorithm differs from its integer counterpart in two respects.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] First, the remainders *r**k* are real numbers, although the quotients *q**k* are integers as before.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Second, the algorithm is not guaranteed to end in a finite number N of steps.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the algorithm does not stop, the fraction *a*/*b* is an irrational number and can be described by an infinite continued fraction [*q*0; *q*1, *q*2, …].
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Examples of infinite continued fractions are the golden ratio *φ* = [1; 1, 1, ...] and the square root of two, √2 = [1; 2, 2, ...].
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] When applied to two arbitrary real numbers, the algorithm is unlikely to stop, since almost all ratios *a*/*b* of two real numbers are irrational.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] An infinite continued fraction may be truncated at a step *k* [*q*0; *q*1, *q*2, ..., *q**k*] to yield an approximation to *a*/*b* that improves as k is increased.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *m*−1 = *n*−2 = 1 and *m*−2 = *n*−1 = 0 are the initial values of the recursion.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Polynomials in a single variable *x* can be added, multiplied and factored into irreducible polynomials, which are the analogs of the prime numbers for integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The greatest common divisor polynomial *g*(*x*) of two polynomials *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*) is defined as the product of their shared irreducible polynomials, which can be identified using the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The basic procedure is similar to that for integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Each quotient polynomial is chosen such that each remainder is either zero or has a degree that is smaller than the degree of its predecessor: deg[*r**k*(*x*)] < deg[*r**k*−1(*x*)].
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the degree is a nonnegative integer, and since it decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm concludes in a finite number of steps.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The last nonzero remainder is the greatest common divisor of the original two polynomials, *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finally, dividing *r*0(*x*) by *r*1(*x*) yields a zero remainder, indicating that *r*1(*x*) is the greatest common divisor polynomial of *a*(*x*) and *b*(*x*), consistent with their factorization.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many of the applications described above for integers carry over to polynomials.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm can be used to solve linear Diophantine equations and Chinese remainder problems for polynomials; continued fractions of polynomials can also be defined.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The polynomial Euclidean algorithm has other applications, such as Sturm chains, a method for counting the zeros of a polynomial that lie inside a given real interval.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This in turn has applications in several areas, such as the Routh–Hurwitz stability criterion in control theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Finally, the coefficients of the polynomials need not be drawn from integers, real numbers or even the complex numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, the coefficients may be drawn from a general field, such as the finite fields GF(*p*) described above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The corresponding conclusions about the Euclidean algorithm and its applications hold even for such polynomials.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Gaussian integers are complex numbers of the form *α* = *u* + *vi*, where u and v are ordinary integers and i is the square root of negative one.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] By defining an analog of the Euclidean algorithm, Gaussian integers can be shown to be uniquely factorizable, by the argument above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This unique factorization is helpful in many applications, such as deriving all Pythagorean triples or proving Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In general, the Euclidean algorithm is convenient in such applications, but not essential; for example, the theorems can often be proven by other arguments.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm developed for two Gaussian integers α and β is nearly the same as that for ordinary integers, but differs in two respects.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where every remainder is strictly smaller than its predecessor: |*r**k*| < |*r**k*−1|.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first difference is that the quotients and remainders are themselves Gaussian integers, and thus are complex numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The quotients *q**k* are generally found by rounding the real and complex parts of the exact ratio (such as the complex number *α*/*β*) to the nearest integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The second difference lies in the necessity of defining how one complex remainder can be "smaller" than another.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] To do this, a norm function *f*(*u* + *vi*) = *u*2 + *v*2 is defined, which converts every Gaussian integer *u* + *vi* into an ordinary integer.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] After each step k of the Euclidean algorithm, the norm of the remainder *f*(*r**k*) is smaller than the norm of the preceding remainder, *f*(*r**k*−1).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since the norm is a nonnegative integer and decreases with every step, the Euclidean algorithm for Gaussian integers ends in a finite number of steps.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The final nonzero remainder is gcd(*α*, *β*), the Gaussian integer of largest norm that divides both α and β; it is unique up to multiplication by a unit, ±1 or ±*i*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many of the other applications of the Euclidean algorithm carry over to Gaussian integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, it can be used to solve linear Diophantine equations and Chinese remainder problems for Gaussian integers; continued fractions of Gaussian integers can also be defined.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A set of elements under two binary operations, denoted as addition and multiplication, is called a Euclidean domain if it forms a commutative ring R and, roughly speaking, if a generalized Euclidean algorithm can be performed on them.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The two operations of such a ring need not be the addition and multiplication of ordinary arithmetic; rather, they can be more general, such as the operations of a mathematical group or monoid.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Nevertheless, these general operations should respect many of the laws governing ordinary arithmetic, such as commutativity, associativity and distributivity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The generalized Euclidean algorithm requires a *Euclidean function*, i.e., a mapping f from R into the set of nonnegative integers such that, for any two nonzero elements a and b in R, there exist q and r in R such that *a* = *qb* + *r* and *f*(*r*) < *f*(*b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Examples of such mappings are the absolute value for integers, the degree for univariate polynomials, and the norm for Gaussian integers above.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The basic principle is that each step of the algorithm reduces *f* inexorably; hence, if f can be reduced only a finite number of times, the algorithm must stop in a finite number of steps.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This principle relies on the well-ordering property of the non-negative integers, which asserts that every non-empty set of non-negative integers has a smallest member.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic applies to any Euclidean domain: Any number from a Euclidean domain can be factored uniquely into irreducible elements.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Any Euclidean domain is a unique factorization domain (UFD), although the converse is not true.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean domains and the UFD's are subclasses of the GCD domains, domains in which a greatest common divisor of two numbers always exists.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In other words, a greatest common divisor may exist (for all pairs of elements in a domain), although it may not be possible to find it using a Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] A Euclidean domain is always a principal ideal domain (PID), an integral domain in which every ideal is a principal ideal.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Again, the converse is not true: not every PID is a Euclidean domain.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The unique factorization of Euclidean domains is useful in many applications.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, the unique factorization of the Gaussian integers is convenient in deriving formulae for all Pythagorean triples and in proving Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Unique factorization was also a key element in an attempted proof of Fermat's Last Theorem published in 1847 by Gabriel Lamé, the same mathematician who analyzed the efficiency of Euclid's algorithm, based on a suggestion of Joseph Liouville.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Lamé's approach required the unique factorization of numbers of the form *x* + *ωy*, where x and y are integers, and *ω* = *e*2*iπ*/*n* is an nth root of 1, that is, *ω**n* = 1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Although this approach succeeds for some values of n (such as *n* = 3, the Eisenstein integers), in general such numbers do *not* factor uniquely.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This failure of unique factorization in some cyclotomic fields led Ernst Kummer to the concept of ideal numbers and, later, Richard Dedekind to ideals.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The quadratic integer rings are helpful to illustrate Euclidean domains.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Quadratic integers are generalizations of the Gaussian integers in which the imaginary unit *i* is replaced by a number ω.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Thus, they have the form *u* + *vω*, where u and v are integers and ω has one of two forms, depending on a parameter D.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If the function f corresponds to a norm function, such as that used to order the Gaussian integers above, then the domain is known as *norm-Euclidean*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The cases *D* = −1 and *D* = −3 yield the Gaussian integers and Eisenstein integers, respectively.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] If f is allowed to be any Euclidean function, then the list of possible values of D for which the domain is Euclidean is not yet known.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The first example of a Euclidean domain that was not norm-Euclidean (with *D* = 69) was published in 1994.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] In 1973, Weinberger proved that a quadratic integer ring with *D* > 0 is Euclidean if, and only if, it is a principal ideal domain, provided that the generalized Riemann hypothesis holds.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] The Euclidean algorithm may be applied to some noncommutative rings such as the set of Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Let α and β represent two elements from such a ring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] They have a common right divisor δ if *α* = *ξδ* and *β* = *ηδ* for some choice of ξ and η in the ring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Similarly, they have a common left divisor if *α* = *dξ* and *β* = *dη* for some choice of ξ and η in the ring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Since multiplication is not commutative, there are two versions of the Euclidean algorithm, one for right divisors and one for left divisors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] where *ψ*0 represents the quotient and *ρ*0 the remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Here the quotient and remainder are chosen so that (if nonzero) the remainder has *N*(*ρ*0) < *N*(*β*) for a "Euclidean function" *N* defined analogously to the Euclidean functions of Euclidean domains in the non-commutative case.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] This equation shows that any common right divisor of α and β is likewise a common divisor of the remainder *ρ*0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] With either choice, the process is repeated as above until the greatest common right or left divisor is identified.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] As in the Euclidean domain, the "size" of the remainder *ρ*0 (formally, its Euclidean function or "norm") must be strictly smaller than β, and there must be only a finite number of possible sizes for *ρ*0, so that the algorithm is guaranteed to terminate.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Many results for the GCD carry over to noncommutative numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For example, Bézout's identity states that the right gcd(*α*, *β*) can be expressed as a linear combination of α and β.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] Bézout's identity can be used to solve Diophantine equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/euclidean-algorithm-p02] For instance, one of the standard proofs of Lagrange's four-square theorem, that every positive integer can be represented as a sum of four squares, is based on quaternion GCDs in this way.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In mathematics, the **greatest common divisor** (**GCD**), also known as **greatest common factor (GCF)**, of two or more integers, which are not all zero, is the largest positive integer that divides each of the integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] For two integers *x*, *y*, the greatest common divisor of *x* and *y* is denoted $\gcd(x,y)$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] For example, the GCD of 8 and 12 is 4, that is, gcd(8, 12) = 4.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In the name "greatest common divisor", the adjective "greatest" may be replaced by "highest", and the word "divisor" may be replaced by "factor", so that other names include **highest common factor (HCF)**, etc.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Historically, other names for the same concept have included **greatest common measure**.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This notion can be extended to polynomials (see *Polynomial greatest common divisor*) and other commutative rings (see *§ In commutative rings* below).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The *greatest common divisor* (GCD) of integers a and b, at least one of which is nonzero, is the greatest positive integer d such that d is a divisor of both a and b; that is, there are integers e and f such that *a* = *de* and *b* = *df*, and d is the largest such integer.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is generally denoted gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] When one of *a* and *b* is zero, the GCD is the absolute value of the nonzero integer: gcd(*a*, 0) = gcd(0, *a*) = |*a*|.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This case is important as the terminating step of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The above definition is unsuitable for defining gcd(0, 0), since there is no greatest integer *n* such that 0 × *n* = 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] However, zero is its own greatest divisor if *greatest* is understood in the context of the divisibility relation, so gcd(0, 0) is commonly defined as 0.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This preserves the usual identities for GCD, and in particular Bézout's identity, namely that gcd(*a*, *b*) generates the same ideal as {*a*, *b*}.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This convention is followed by many computer algebra systems.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Nonetheless, some authors leave gcd(0, 0) undefined.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is their greatest positive common divisor in the preorder relation of divisibility.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the common divisors of a and b are exactly the divisors of their GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This is commonly proved by using either Euclid's lemma, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, or the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This is the meaning of "greatest" that is used for the generalizations of the concept of GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Computing all divisors of the two numbers in this way is usually not efficient, especially for large numbers that have many divisors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Much more efficient methods are described in *§ Calculation*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Two numbers are called relatively prime, or coprime, if their greatest common divisor equals 1.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] For example, a 24-by-60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: 1-by-1 squares, 2-by-2 squares, 3-by-3 squares, 4-by-4 squares, 6-by-6 squares or 12-by-12 squares.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, 12 is the greatest common divisor of 24 and 60.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] A 24-by-60 rectangular area can thus be divided into a grid of 12-by-12 squares, with two squares along one edge (24/12 = 2) and five squares along the other (60/12 = 5).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor is useful for reducing fractions to the lowest terms.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Greatest common divisors can be computed by determining the prime factorizations of the two numbers and comparing factors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In practice, this method is only feasible for small numbers, as computing prime factorizations takes too long.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The method introduced by Euclid for computing greatest common divisors is based on the fact that, given two positive integers a and b such that *a* > *b*, the common divisors of a and b are the same as the common divisors of *a* – *b* and b.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] So, Euclid's method for computing the greatest common divisor of two positive integers consists of replacing the larger number with the difference of the numbers, and repeating this until the two numbers are equal: that is their greatest common divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This method can be very slow if one number is much larger than the other.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] So, the variant that follows is generally preferred.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] A more efficient method is the *Euclidean algorithm*, a variant in which the difference of the two numbers a and b is replaced by the *remainder* of the Euclidean division (also called *division with remainder*) of a by b.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Denoting this remainder as *a* mod *b*, the algorithm replaces (*a*, *b*) with (*b*, *a* mod *b*) repeatedly until the pair is (*d*, 0), where d is the greatest common divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is a variant of Euclid's algorithm that is specially adapted to the binary representation of the numbers, which is used in most computers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm differs from Euclid's algorithm essentially by dividing by two every even number that is encountered during the computation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Its efficiency results from the fact that, in binary representation, testing parity consists of testing the right-most digit, and dividing by two consists of removing the right-most digit.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The method is as follows, starting with *a* and *b* that are the two positive integers whose GCD is sought.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] If *a* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] If *b* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Step 1 determines d as the highest power of 2 that divides *a* and *b*, and thus their greatest common divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] None of the steps changes the set of the odd common divisors of *a* and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This shows that when the algorithm stops, the result is correct.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The algorithm stops eventually, since each steps divides at least one of the operands by at least 2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Moreover, the number of divisions by 2 and thus the number of subtractions is at most the total number of digits.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is particularly easy to implement and particularly efficient on binary computers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The square in this complexity comes from the fact that division by 2 and subtraction take a time that is proportional to the number of bits of the input.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity is usually given in terms of the length *n* of the input.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Lehmer's algorithm is based on the observation that the initial quotients produced by Euclid's algorithm can be determined based on only the first few digits; this is useful for numbers that are larger than a computer word.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In essence, one extracts initial digits, typically forming one or two computer words, and runs Euclid's algorithms on these smaller numbers, as long as it is guaranteed that the quotients are the same with those that would be obtained with the original numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The quotients are collected into a small 2-by-2 transformation matrix (a matrix of single-word integers) to reduce the original numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This process is repeated until numbers are small enough that the binary algorithm (see below) is more efficient.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm improves speed, because it reduces the number of operations on very large numbers, and can use hardware arithmetic for most operations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In fact, most of the quotients are very small, so a fair number of steps of the Euclidean algorithm can be collected in a 2-by-2 matrix of single-word integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] When Lehmer's algorithm encounters a quotient that is too large, it must fall back to one iteration of Euclidean algorithm, with a Euclidean division of large numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] but more commonly the LCM is computed from the GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] which generalizes to *a* and *b* rational numbers or commensurable real numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] which is a function that can be evaluated for complex *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] is an entire function in the variable *b* for all positive integers *a* where *c**d*(*k*) is Ramanujan's sum.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity of the computation of greatest common divisors has been widely studied.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] If one uses the Euclidean algorithm and the elementary algorithms for multiplication and division, the computation of the greatest common divisor of two integers of at most n bits is *O*(*n*2).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the computation of greatest common divisor has, up to a constant factor, the same complexity as the multiplication.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] However, if a fast multiplication algorithm is used, one may modify the Euclidean algorithm for improving the complexity, but the computation of a greatest common divisor becomes slower than the multiplication.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] More precisely, if the multiplication of two integers of *n* bits takes a time of *T*(*n*), then the fastest known algorithm for greatest common divisor has a complexity *O*(*T*(*n*) log *n*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This implies that the fastest known algorithm has a complexity of *O*(*n* (log *n*)2).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Previous complexities are valid for the usual models of computation, specifically multitape Turing machines and random-access machines.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The computation of the greatest common divisors belongs thus to the class of problems solvable in quasilinear time.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] *A fortiori*, the corresponding decision problem belongs to the class P of problems solvable in polynomial time.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD problem is not known to be in NC, and so there is no known way to parallelize it efficiently; nor is it known to be P-complete, which would imply that it is unlikely to be possible to efficiently parallelize GCD computation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Shallcross et al. showed that a related problem (EUGCD, determining the remainder sequence arising during the Euclidean algorithm) is NC-equivalent to the problem of integer linear programming with two variables; if either problem is in **NC** or is **P-complete**, the other is as well.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Since **NC** contains NL, it is also unknown whether a space-efficient algorithm for computing the GCD exists, even for nondeterministic Turing machines.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Although the problem is not known to be in **NC**, parallel algorithms asymptotically faster than the Euclidean algorithm exist; the fastest known deterministic algorithm is by Chor and Goldreich, which (in the CRCW-PRAM model) can solve the problem in *O*(*n*/log *n*) time with *n*1+*ε* processors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Randomized algorithms can solve the problem in *O*((log *n*)2) time on $O\left(e^{\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)$ processors (this is superpolynomial).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This formula is often used to compute least common multiples: one first computes the GCD with Euclid's algorithm and then divides the product of the given numbers by their GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Nymann showed that *k* integers, chosen independently and uniformly from {1, ..., *n*}, are coprime with probability 1/*ζ*(*k*) as *n* goes to infinity, where *ζ* refers to the Riemann zeta function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] (See coprime for a derivation.) This result was extended in 1987 to show that the probability that *k* random integers have greatest common divisor *d* is *d*−*k*/ζ(*k*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Using this information, the expected value of the greatest common divisor function can be seen (informally) to not exist when *k* = 2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This last summation is the harmonic series, which diverges.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] For *k* = 3, this is approximately equal to 1.3684.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The notion of greatest common divisor can more generally be defined for elements of an arbitrary commutative ring, although in general there need not exist one for every pair of elements.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] With this definition, two elements a and b may very well have several greatest common divisors, or none at all.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] If R is an integral domain, then any two GCDs of a and b must be associate elements, since by definition either one must divide the other.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Indeed, if a GCD exists, any one of its associates is a GCD as well.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Existence of a GCD is not assured in arbitrary integral domains.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] However, if R is a unique factorization domain or any other GCD domain, then any two elements have a GCD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] The elements 2 and $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ are two maximal common divisors (that is, any common divisor which is a multiple of 2 is associated to 2, the same holds for $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ , but they are not associated, so there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] Corresponding to the Bézout property we may, in any commutative ring, consider the collection of elements of the form *pa* + *qb*, where p and q range over the ring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] This is the ideal generated by a and b, and is denoted simply (*a*, *b*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] In a ring all of whose ideals are principal (a principal ideal domain or PID), this ideal will be identical with the set of multiples of some ring element *d*; then this d is a greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/greatest-common-divisor] But the ideal (*a*, *b*) can be useful even when there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In mathematics, **modular arithmetic** is a system of arithmetic operations for integers, differing from the usual ones in that numbers "wrap around" when reaching or exceeding a certain value, called the **modulus**.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The modern approach to number theory using modular arithmetic was developed by Carl Friedrich Gauss in his book *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*, published in 1801.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] A familiar setting exhibiting modular arithmetic is the hour hand on a 12-hour clock.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] If the hour hand points to 7 now, then 8 hours later it will point to 3.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Ordinary addition would result in 7 + 8 = 15, but 15 reads as 3 on the clock face.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] This is because the hour hand makes one rotation every 12 hours and the hour number starts over when the hour hand passes 12.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] We say that 15 is *congruent* to 3 modulo 12, and we write 15 ≡ 3 (mod 12), so 7 + 8 ≡ 3 (mod 12).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Similarly, if one waits 8 hours and then 8 more hours (thus 16 hours in total), the clock will show the same time change as if one waited 4 hours.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] This is reflected by the identity 2 × 8 ≡ 4 (mod 12).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] After a wait of exactly 12 hours, the hour hand will be right where it started, so 12 acts as 0; one writes 12 ≡ 0 (mod 12).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Congruence modulo m is a congruence relation, meaning that it is an equivalence relation compatible with addition, subtraction, and multiplication.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The parentheses mean that (mod *m*) applies to the entire equation, not just to the right-hand side (here, b).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The congruence relation *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*) may be rewritten as $\exists k\in \mathbb {Z} \quad a=km+b,$ explicitly showing its relationship with Euclidean division.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] However, the *b* here need not be the remainder in the division of *a* by *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Rather, *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*) asserts that *a* and *b* have the same remainder when divided by *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] where 0 ≤ *r* < *m* is the common remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] We recover the previous relation (*a* − *b* = *k m*) by subtracting these two expressions and setting *k* = *p* − *q*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Because the congruence modulo m is defined by the divisibility by m and because −1 is a unit in the ring of integers, a number is divisible by −*m* exactly if it is divisible by m.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] This means that every non-zero integer m may be taken as a modulus.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] because the difference is 38 − 14 = 24 = 2 × 12, a multiple of 12.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Equivalently, 38 and 14 have the same remainder 2 when divided by 12.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The definition of congruence also applies to negative values.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] If *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*), then it is generally false that *ka* ≡ *kb* (mod *m*).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The last rule can be used to move modular arithmetic into division.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The multiplicative inverse *x* ≡ *a*−1 (mod *m*) may be efficiently computed by solving Bézout's equation *a x* + *m y* = 1 for *x*, *y*, by using the Extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In particular, if *p* is a prime number, then *a* is coprime with *p* for every *a* such that 0 < *a* < *p*; thus a multiplicative inverse exists for all *a* that is not congruent to zero modulo *p*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The congruence relation is an equivalence relation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The equivalence class modulo m of an integer *a* is the set of all integers of the form *a* + *k m*, where k is any integer.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It is called the **congruence class** or **residue class** of *a* modulo *m*, and may be denoted (*a* mod *m*), or as *a* or [*a*] when the modulus *m* is known from the context.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Each residue class modulo *m* contains exactly one integer in the range $0,...,|m|-1$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Thus, these $|m|$ integers are representatives of their respective residue classes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It is generally easier to work with integers than sets of integers; that is, the representatives most often considered, rather than their residue classes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Consequently, (*a* mod *m*) denotes generally the unique integer r such that 0 ≤ *r* < *m* and *r* ≡ *a* (mod *m*); it is called the **residue** of *a* modulo *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In particular, (*a* mod *m*) = (*b* mod *m*) is equivalent to *a* ≡ *b* (mod *m*), and this explains why "=" is often used instead of "≡" in this context.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Each residue class modulo *m* may be represented by any one of its members, although we usually represent each residue class by the smallest nonnegative integer which belongs to that class (since this is the proper remainder which results from division).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Any two members of different residue classes modulo *m* are incongruent modulo *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Furthermore, every integer belongs to one and only one residue class modulo *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The set of integers {0, 1, 2, ..., *m* − 1} is called the **least residue system modulo *m***.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Any set of *m* integers, no two of which are congruent modulo *m*, is called a **complete residue system modulo *m***.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The least residue system is a complete residue system, and a complete residue system is simply a set containing precisely one representative of each residue class modulo *m*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] For example, the least residue system modulo 4 is {0, 1, 2, 3}.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Given the Euler's totient function *φ*(*m*), any set of *φ*(*m*) integers that are relatively prime to *m* and mutually incongruent under modulus *m* is called a **reduced residue system modulo *m***.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The set {5, 15} from above, for example, is an instance of a reduced residue system modulo 4.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Covering systems represent yet another type of residue system that may contain residues with varying moduli.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In the context of this paragraph, the modulus *m* is almost always taken as positive.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The set of all congruence classes modulo *m* is a ring called the **ring of integers modulo *m***, and is denoted ${\textstyle \mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z} }$ , $\mathbb {Z} /(m)$ , $\mathbb {Z} /m$ , or $\mathbb {Z} _{m}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The ring $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is fundamental to various branches of mathematics (see *§ Applications* below).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] When *m* = 1, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is the zero ring; when *m* = 0, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is not an empty set; rather, it is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z}$ , since *a*0 = {*a*}.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The properties given before imply that, with these operations, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is a commutative ring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] as in the arithmetic for the 24-hour clock.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Under addition, $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is a cyclic group.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] All finite cyclic groups are isomorphic with $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ for some m.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The ring of integers modulo *m* is a field; that is, every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse, if and only if *m* is prime.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] If *m* = *p**k* is a prime power with *k* > 1, there exists a unique (up to isomorphism) finite field $\mathrm {GF} (m)=\mathbb {F} _{m}$ with *m* elements, which is *not* isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ , which fails to be a field because it has zero-divisors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] If *m* > 1, $(\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z} )^{\times }$ denotes the multiplicative group of the integers modulo *m* that are invertible.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It consists of the congruence classes *a**m*, where *a* is coprime to *m*; these are precisely the classes possessing a multiplicative inverse.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] They form an abelian group under multiplication; its order is *φ*(*m*), where φ is Euler's totient function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In pure mathematics, modular arithmetic is one of the foundations of number theory, touching on almost every aspect of its study, and it is also used extensively in group theory, ring theory, knot theory, and abstract algebra.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In applied mathematics, it is used in computer algebra, cryptography, computer science, chemistry and the visual and musical arts.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] A very practical application is to calculate checksums within serial number identifiers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] For example, International Standard Book Number (ISBN) uses modulo 11 (for 10-digit ISBN) or modulo 10 (for 13-digit ISBN) arithmetic for error detection.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Likewise, International Bank Account Numbers (IBANs) use modulo 97 arithmetic to spot user input errors in bank account numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] RSA and Diffie–Hellman use modular exponentiation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In computer algebra, modular arithmetic is commonly used to limit the size of integer coefficients in intermediate calculations and data.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It is used in polynomial factorization, a problem for which all known efficient algorithms use modular arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It is used by the most efficient implementations of polynomial greatest common divisor, exact linear algebra and Gröbner basis algorithms over the integers and the rational numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In computer science, modular arithmetic is often applied in bitwise operations and other operations involving fixed-width, cyclic data structures.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The modulo operation, as implemented in many programming languages and calculators, is an application of modular arithmetic that is often used in this context.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The logical operator XOR sums 2 bits, modulo 2.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The use of long division to turn a fraction into a repeating decimal in any base *b* is equivalent to modular multiplication of *b* modulo the denominator.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In music, arithmetic modulo 12 is used in the consideration of the system of twelve-tone equal temperament, where octave and enharmonic equivalency occurs (that is, pitches in a 1:2 or 2:1 ratio are equivalent, and C-sharp is considered the same as D-flat).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] The method of casting out nines offers a quick check of decimal arithmetic computations performed by hand.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] It is based on modular arithmetic modulo 9, and specifically on the crucial property that 10 ≡ 1 (mod 9).
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Arithmetic modulo 7 is used in algorithms that determine the day of the week for a given date.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] In particular, Zeller's congruence and the Doomsday algorithm make heavy use of modulo-7 arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] More generally, modular arithmetic also has application in disciplines such as politics (for example, apportionment), economics (for example, game theory) and other areas of the social sciences, where proportional division and allocation of resources plays a central part of the analysis.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Since modular arithmetic has such a wide range of applications, it is important to know how hard it is to solve a system of congruences.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] A linear system of congruences can be solved in polynomial time with a form of Gaussian elimination, for details see linear congruence theorem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Algorithms, such as Montgomery reduction, also exist to allow simple arithmetic operations, such as multiplication and exponentiation modulo *m*, to be performed efficiently on large numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Some operations, like finding a discrete logarithm or a quadratic congruence appear to be as hard as integer factorization and thus are a starting point for cryptographic algorithms and encryption.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] These problems might be NP-intermediate.
[src:euclidean-gcd/modular-arithmetic] Solving a system of non-linear modular arithmetic equations is NP-complete.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Integers can be considered either in themselves or as solutions to equations (Diophantine geometry).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Questions in number theory can often be understood through the study of analytical objects, such as the Riemann zeta function, that encode properties of the integers, primes or other number-theoretic objects in some fashion (analytic number theory).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One may also study real numbers in relation to rational numbers, as for instance how irrational numbers can be approximated by fractions (Diophantine approximation).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number theory is one of the oldest branches of mathematics alongside geometry.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One quirk of number theory is that it deals with statements that are simple to understand but are very difficult to solve.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Examples of this are Fermat's Last Theorem, which was proved 358 years after the original formulation, and Goldbach's conjecture, which remains unsolved since the 18th century.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number theory is the branch of mathematics that studies integers and their properties and relations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The integers comprise a set that extends the set of natural numbers $\{1,2,3,\dots \}$ to include number 0 and the negation of natural numbers $\{-1,-2,-3,\dots \}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number theorists study prime numbers as well as the properties of mathematical objects constructed from integers (for example, rational numbers), or defined as generalizations of the integers (for example, algebraic integers).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number theory is closely related to arithmetic and some authors use the terms as synonyms.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] However, the word "arithmetic" is used today to mean the study of numerical operations and extends to the real numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In a more specific sense, number theory is restricted to the study of integers and focuses on their properties and relationships.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Traditionally, it is known as higher arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] By the early twentieth century, the term *number theory* had been widely adopted.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The term number means whole numbers, which refers to either the natural numbers or the integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies aspects of integers that can be investigated using elementary methods such as elementary proofs.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Analytic number theory, by contrast, relies on complex numbers and techniques from analysis and calculus.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Algebraic number theory employs algebraic structures such as fields and rings to analyze the properties of and relations between numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Geometric number theory uses concepts from geometry to study numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Further branches of number theory are probabilistic number theory, combinatorial number theory, computational number theory, and applied number theory, which examines the application of number theory to science and technology.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In recorded history, knowledge of numbers existed in the ancient civilisations of Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, and India.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The earliest historical find of an arithmetical nature is the Plimpton 322, dated c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It is a broken clay tablet that contains a list of Pythagorean triples, that is, integers $(a,b,c)$ such that $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The triples are too numerous and too large to have been obtained by brute force.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The table's layout suggests that it was constructed by means of what amounts, in modern language, to the identity $\left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x-{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2}+1=\left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2},$ which is implicit in routine Old Babylonian exercises.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It has been suggested instead that the table was a source of numerical examples for school problems.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Plimpton 322 tablet is the only surviving evidence of what today would be called number theory within Babylonian mathematics, though a kind of Babylonian algebra was much more developed.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Although other civilizations probably influenced Greek mathematics at the beginning, all evidence of such borrowings appear relatively late, and it is likely that Greek *arithmētikḗ*, the theoretical or philosophical study of numbers, is an indigenous tradition.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Ancient Greek mathematicians conventionally separated numbers (mostly positive integers but occasionally rationals) from magnitudes or lengths, with only the former being the subject of arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A keen interest in divisibility is found in early Greek arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Pythagoreans often attributed mystical qualities to perfect and amicable numbers, and dedicated time to the study polygonal or figurate numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Later, Euclid devoted part of his *Elements* to topics that belong to elementary number theory, including prime numbers and divisibility.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He gave the Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor of two numbers and a proof implying the infinitude of primes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Building on the works of the earlier Pythagoreans, Nicomachus of Gerasa wrote an *Introduction to Arithmetic* that was to be influential in later centuries, while Theon of Smyrna's *Mathematics Useful For Understanding Plato* discusses the idea of congruences.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The most important late antique author was arguably Diophantus of Alexandria, who probably lived in the 3rd century AD.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He wrote the *Arithmetica*, a collection of worked-out problems where the task is invariably to find rational solutions to a system of polynomial equations, usually of the form $f(x,y)=z^{2}$ or $f(x,y,z)=w^{2}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In modern parlance, Diophantine equations are polynomial equations to which rational or integer solutions are sought.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] After the fall of Rome, development shifted to Asia, albeit intermittently.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The Chinese remainder theorem appears as an exercise in *Sunzi Suanjing* (between the third and fifth centuries).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The result was later generalized with a complete solution called *Da-yan-shu* (大衍術) in Qin Jiushao's 1247 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections.* There is also some numerical mysticism in Chinese mathematics, but, unlike that of the Pythagoreans, it seems to have led nowhere.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Brahmagupta (628 AD) started the systematic study of indefinite quadratic equations—in particular, the Pell equation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A general procedure for solving Pell's equation was probably found by Jayadeva; the earliest surviving exposition appears in Bhāskara II's Bīja-gaṇita (twelfth century).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In the early ninth century, the caliph al-Ma'mun ordered translations of many Greek mathematical works and at least one Sanskrit work.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Diophantus's main work, the *Arithmetica*, was translated into Arabic by Qusta ibn Luqa (820–912).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Part of the treatise *al-Fakhri* (by al-Karajī, 953 – c.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] According to Rashed Roshdi, Al-Karajī's contemporary Ibn al-Haytham knew what would later be called Wilson's theorem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Other than a treatise on squares in arithmetic progression by Fibonacci no number theory to speak of was done in western Europe during the Middle Ages.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Matters started to change in Europe in the late Renaissance, thanks to a renewed study of the works of Greek antiquity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A catalyst was the textual emendation and translation into Latin of Diophantus' *Arithmetica*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] French mathematician Pierre de Fermat (1607–1665) never published his writings but communicated through correspondence and wrote in marginal notes instead.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] His contributions to number theory brought renewed interest in the field in Europe.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He conjectured Fermat's little theorem, a basic result in modular arithmetic, and Fermat's Last Theorem, as well as proved Fermat's right triangle theorem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He also studied prime numbers, the four-square theorem, and Pell's equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The interest of Leonhard Euler (1707–1783) in number theory was first spurred in 1729, when a friend of his, the amateur Christian Goldbach, pointed him towards some of Fermat's work on the subject.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This has been called the "rebirth" of modern number theory, after Fermat's relative lack of success in getting his contemporaries' attention for the subject.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He proved Fermat's assertions, including Fermat's little theorem; made initial work towards a proof that every integer is the sum of four squares; and specific cases of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He wrote on the link between continued fractions and Pell's equation.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He made the first steps towards analytic number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Three European contemporaries continued the work in elementary number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Joseph-Louis Lagrange (1736–1813) gave full proofs of the four-square theorem, Wilson's theorem, and developed the basic theory of Pell's equations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Adrien-Marie Legendre (1752–1833) stated the law of quadratic reciprocity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He also conjectured what amounts to the prime number theorem and Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In his old age, he was the first to prove Fermat's Last Theorem for $n=5$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Carl Friedrich Gauss (1777–1855) wrote *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* (1801), which had an immense influence in the area of number theory and set its agenda for much of the 19th century.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Gauss proved in this work the law of quadratic reciprocity and developed the theory of quadratic forms.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He also introduced some basic notation to congruences and devoted a section to computational matters, including primality tests.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He established a link between roots of unity and number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In this way, Gauss arguably made forays towards Évariste Galois's work and the area algebraic number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Algebraic number theory may be said to start with the study of reciprocity and cyclotomy, but truly came into its own with the development of abstract algebra and early ideal theory and valuation theory; see below.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A conventional starting point for analytic number theory is Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions (1837), whose proof introduced L-functions and involved some asymptotic analysis and a limiting process on a real variable.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The first use of analytic ideas in number theory actually goes back to Euler (1730s), who used formal power series and non-rigorous (or implicit) limiting arguments.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The American Mathematical Society awards the *Cole Prize in Number Theory*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Moreover, number theory is one of the three mathematical subdisciplines rewarded by the *Fermat Prize*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory deals with the topics in number theory by means of basic methods in arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Its primary subjects of study are divisibility, factorization, and primality, as well as congruences in modular arithmetic.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Other topics in elementary number theory include Diophantine equations, continued fractions, integer partitions, and Diophantine approximations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Arithmetic is the study of numerical operations and investigates how numbers are combined and transformed using the arithmetic operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, exponentiation, extraction of roots, and logarithms.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Multiplication, for instance, is an operation that combines two numbers, referred to as factors, to form a single number, termed the product, such as $2\times 3=6$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Divisibility is a property between two nonzero integers related to division.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] An integer a is said to be divisible by a nonzero integer b if a is a multiple of b ; that is, if there exists an integer q such that $a=bq$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] An equivalent formulation is that b divides a and is denoted by a vertical bar, which in this case is $b|a$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Conversely, if this were not the case, then a would not be divided evenly by b , resulting in a remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Euclid's division lemma asserts that a and b can generally be written as $a=bq+r$ , where the remainder r accounts for the smallest positive leftover quantity.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies divisibility rules in order to quickly identify if a given integer is divisible by a fixed divisor.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For instance, it is known that any integer is divisible by 3 if its decimal digit sum is divisible by 3.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A common divisor of several nonzero integers is an integer that divides all of them.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The greatest common divisor (gcd) is the largest of such divisors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Two integers are said to be coprime or relatively prime to one another if their greatest common divisor, and simultaneously their only divisor, is 1 .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The Euclidean algorithm computes the greatest common divisor of two integers $a,b$ by means of repeatedly applying the division lemma and shifting the divisor and remainder after every step.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The algorithm can be extended to solve a special case of linear Diophantine equations $ax+by=1$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A Diophantine equation has several unknowns and integer coefficients.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Another kind of Diophantine equation is described in the Pythagorean theorem, $x^{2}+y^{2}=z^{2}$ , whose solutions are called Pythagorean triples if they are all integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Another kind of expression is the continued fraction, which writes a sum of an integer and a fraction whose denominator is another such sum.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory studies the divisibility properties of integers such as parity (even and odd numbers), prime numbers, and perfect numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Important number-theoretic functions include the divisor-counting function, the divisor summatory function and its modifications, and Euler's totient function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A prime number is an integer greater than 1 whose only positive divisors are 1 and the prime itself.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A positive integer greater than 1 that is not prime is called a composite number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Euclid's theorem demonstrates that there are infinitely many prime numbers that comprise the set $\{2,3,5,7,11,\cdots \}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The sieve of Eratosthenes was devised as an efficient algorithm for identifying all primes up to a given natural number by eliminating all composite numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Factorization is a method of expressing a number as a product.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Specifically in number theory, integer factorization is the decomposition of an integer into a product of integers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The process of repeatedly applying this procedure until all factors are prime is known as prime factorization.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A fundamental property of primes is shown in Euclid's lemma.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It is a consequence of the lemma that if a prime divides a product of integers, then that prime divides at least one of the factors in the product.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The unique factorization theorem is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic that relates to prime factorization.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The theorem states that every integer greater than 1 can be factorised into a product of prime numbers and that this factorisation is unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, $120$ is expressed uniquely as $2\times 2\times 2\times 3\times 5$ or simply $2^{3}\times 3\times 5$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Modular arithmetic works with finite sets of integers and introduces the concepts of congruence and residue classes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A congruence of two integers $a,b$ modulo n (a positive integer called the modulus) is an equivalence relation whereby $n|(a-b)$ is true.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Performing Euclidean division on both a and n , and on b and n , yields the same remainder.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This written as ${\textstyle a\equiv b{\pmod {n}}}$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In a manner analogous to the 12-hour clock, the sum of 4 and 9 is equal to $13$ , yet congruent to 1 .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A residue class modulo n is a set that contains all integers congruent to a specified r modulo n .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, $6\mathbb {Z} +1$ contains all multiples of 6 incremented by 1 .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Modular arithmetic provides a range of formulas for rapidly solving congruences of very large powers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] An influential theorem is Fermat's little theorem, which states that if a prime p is coprime to some integer a , then ${\textstyle a^{p-1}\equiv 1{\pmod {p}}}$ is true.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Euler's theorem extends this to assert that every integer n satisfies the congruence $a^{\varphi (n)}\equiv 1{\pmod {n}},$ where Euler's totient function $\varphi$ counts all positive integers up to n that are coprime to n .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Modular arithmetic also provides formulas that are used to solve congruences with unknowns in a similar vein to equation solving in algebra, such as the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Analytic number theory, in contrast to elementary number theory, relies on complex numbers and techniques from analysis and calculus.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It studies the distribution of primes, behavior of number-theoretic functions, and irrational numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number theory has the reputation of being a field many of whose results can be stated to the layperson.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] At the same time, many of the proofs of these results are not particularly accessible, in part because the range of tools they use is, if anything, unusually broad within mathematics.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The following are examples of problems in analytic number theory: the prime number theorem, the Goldbach conjecture, the twin prime conjecture, the Hardy–Littlewood conjectures, the Waring problem and the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Some of the most important tools of analytic number theory are the circle method, sieve methods and L-functions (or, rather, the study of their properties).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The theory of modular forms (and, more generally, automorphic forms) also occupies an increasingly central place in the toolbox of analytic number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Analysis is the branch of mathematics that studies the limit, defined as the value to which a sequence or function tends as the argument (or index) approaches a specific value.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In the context of functions, the limit of ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{x}}}$ as x approaches infinity is 0 .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The complex numbers extend the real numbers with the imaginary unit i defined as the solution to $i^{2}=-1$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Every complex number can be expressed as $x+iy$ , where x is called the real part and y is called the imaginary part.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The distribution of primes, described by the function $\pi$ that counts all primes up to a given real number, is unpredictable and is a major subject of study in number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary formulas for a partial sequence of primes, including Euler's prime-generating polynomials have been developed.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] However, these cease to function as the primes become too large.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The prime number theorem in analytic number theory provides a formalisation of the notion that prime numbers appear less commonly as their numerical value increases.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One distribution states, informally, that the function ${\frac {x}{\log(x)}}$ approximates $\pi (x)$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Another distribution involves an offset logarithmic integral which converges to $\pi (x)$ more quickly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The zeta function has been demonstrated to be connected to the distribution of primes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] He established a connection between the nontrivial zeroes and the prime-counting function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In what is now recognised as the unsolved Riemann hypothesis, a solution to it would imply direct consequences for understanding the distribution of primes.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One may ask analytic questions about algebraic numbers, and use analytic means to answer such questions; it is thus that algebraic and analytic number theory intersect.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, one may define prime ideals (generalizations of prime numbers in the field of algebraic numbers) and ask how many prime ideals there are up to a certain size.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This question can be answered by means of an examination of Dedekind zeta functions, which are generalizations of the Riemann zeta function, a key analytic object at the roots of the subject.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This is an example of a general procedure in analytic number theory: deriving information about the distribution of a sequence (here, prime ideals or prime numbers) from the analytic behavior of an appropriately constructed complex-valued function.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory works with *elementary proofs*, a term that excludes the use of complex numbers but may include basic analysis.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, the prime number theorem was first proven using complex analysis in 1896, but an elementary proof was found only in 1949 by Erdős and Selberg.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, proofs based on complex Tauberian theorems, such as Wiener–Ikehara, are often seen as quite enlightening but not elementary despite using Fourier analysis, not complex analysis.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Here as elsewhere, an *elementary* proof may be longer and more difficult for most readers than a more advanced proof.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Some subjects generally considered to be part of analytic number theory (e.g., sieve theory) are better covered by the second rather than the first definition.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Small sieves, for instance, use little analysis and yet still belong to analytic number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] An *algebraic number* is any complex number that is a solution to some polynomial equation $f(x)=0$ with rational coefficients; for example, every solution x of $x^{5}+(11/2)x^{3}-7x^{2}+9=0$ is an algebraic number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Fields of algebraic numbers are also called *algebraic number fields*, or shortly *number fields*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Algebraic number theory studies algebraic number fields.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It could be argued that the simplest kind of number fields, namely quadratic fields, were already studied by Gauss, as the discussion of quadratic forms in *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* can be restated in terms of ideals and norms in quadratic fields.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] However, neither Bhāskara nor Gauss knew of number fields as such.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The grounds of the subject were set in the late nineteenth century, when *ideal numbers*, the *theory of ideals* and *valuation theory* were introduced; these are three complementary ways of dealing with the lack of unique factorization in algebraic number fields.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Number fields are often studied as extensions of smaller number fields: a field *L* is said to be an *extension* of a field *K* if *L* contains *K*.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] (For example, the complex numbers *C* are an extension of the reals *R*, and the reals *R* are an extension of the rationals *Q*.) Classifying the possible extensions of a given number field is a difficult and partially open problem.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Abelian extensions—that is, extensions *L* of *K* such that the Galois group Gal(*L*/*K*) of *L* over *K* is an abelian group—are relatively well understood.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Their classification was the object of the programme of class field theory, which was initiated in the late nineteenth century (partly by Kronecker and Eisenstein) and carried out largely in 1900–1950.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] An example of an active area of research in algebraic number theory is Iwasawa theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The Langlands program, one of the main current large-scale research plans in mathematics, is sometimes described as an attempt to generalise class field theory to non-abelian extensions of number fields.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The central problem of Diophantine geometry is to determine when a Diophantine equation has integer or rational solutions, and if it does, how many.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The approach taken is to think of the solutions of an equation as a geometric object.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For example, an equation in two variables defines a curve in the plane.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] More generally, an equation or system of equations in two or more variables defines a curve, a surface, or some other such object in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In Diophantine geometry, one asks whether there are any *rational points* (points all of whose coordinates are rationals) or *integral points* (points all of whose coordinates are integers) on the curve or surface.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] If there are any such points, the next step is to ask how many there are and how they are distributed.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A basic question in this direction is whether there are finitely or infinitely many rational points on a given curve or surface.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Consider, for instance, the Pythagorean equation $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ .
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One would like to know its rational solutions, namely $(x,y)$ such that *x* and *y* are both rational.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This is the same as asking for all integer solutions to $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ ; any solution to the latter equation gives us a solution $x=a/c$ , $y=b/c$ to the former.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It is also the same as asking for all points with rational coordinates on the curve described by $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ (a circle of radius 1 centered on the origin).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The rephrasing of questions on equations in terms of points on curves is felicitous.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The finiteness or not of the number of rational or integer points on an algebraic curve (that is, rational or integer solutions to an equation $f(x,y)=0$ , where f is a polynomial in two variables) depends crucially on the genus of the curve.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] A major achievement of this approach is Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem, for which other geometrical notions are just as crucial.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] There is also the closely linked area of Diophantine approximations: given a number x , determine how well it can be approximated by rational numbers.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] One seeks approximations that are good relative to the amount of space required to write the rational number: call $a/q$ (with $\gcd(a,q)=1$ ) a good approximation to x if $|x-a/q|<{\frac {1}{q^{c}}}$ , where c is large.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This question is of special interest if x is an algebraic number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] If x cannot be approximated well, then some equations do not have integer or rational solutions.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Moreover, several concepts (especially that of height) are critical both in Diophantine geometry and in the study of Diophantine approximations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This question is also of special interest in transcendental number theory: if a number can be approximated better than any algebraic number, then it is a transcendental number.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It is by this argument that π and e have been shown to be transcendental.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Diophantine geometry should not be confused with the geometry of numbers, which is a collection of graphical methods for answering certain questions in algebraic number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Arithmetic geometry is a contemporary term for the same domain covered by Diophantine geometry, particularly when one wishes to emphasize the connections to modern algebraic geometry (for example, in Faltings' theorem) rather than to techniques in Diophantine approximations.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Probabilistic number theory starts with questions such as the following: Take an integer n at random between one and a million.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] (this is just another way of asking how many primes there are between one and a million).
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] How many prime divisors will n have on average?
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] What is the probability that it will have many more or many fewer divisors or prime divisors than the average?
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Should it be possible to write large integers as sums of elements of A ?
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] There are two main questions: "Can this be computed?" and "Can it be computed rapidly?" Anyone can test whether a number is prime or, if it is not, split it into prime factors; doing so rapidly is another matter.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Fast algorithms for testing primality are now known, but, in spite of much work (both theoretical and practical), no truly fast algorithm for factoring.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] For a long time, number theory in general, and the study of prime numbers in particular, was seen as the canonical example of pure mathematics, with no applications outside of mathematics other than the use of prime numbered gear teeth to distribute wear evenly.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In particular, number theorists such as British mathematician G.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Hardy prided themselves on doing work that had absolutely no military significance.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] The number-theorist Leonard Dickson (1874–1954) said "Thank God that number theory is unsullied by any application".
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Such a view is no longer applicable to number theory.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] This vision of the purity of number theory was shattered in the 1970s, when it was publicly announced that prime numbers could be used as the basis for the creation of public-key cryptography algorithms.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Schemes such as RSA are based on the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers into their prime factors.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] These applications have led to significant study of algorithms for computing with prime numbers, and in particular of primality testing, methods for determining whether a given number is prime.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Prime numbers are also used in computing for checksums, hash tables, and pseudorandom number generators.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] In 1974, Donald Knuth said "virtually every theorem in elementary number theory arises in a natural, motivated way in connection with the problem of making computers do high-speed numerical calculations".
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] Elementary number theory is taught in discrete mathematics courses for computer scientists.
[src:euclidean-gcd/number-theory] It also has applications to the continuous in numerical analysis.
